Colombia Bond Yields Fall to Four-Month Low on Slower Inflation

-- B y   A n d r e a   J a r a m i l l o
-- 
2011-05-06T14:06:32Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-06/colombia-bond-yields-fall-to-four-month-low-on-slower-inflation.html
Colombia ’s bonds rose, pushing yields
to their lowest level in almost four months, after April
inflation came in lower than forecast.  The yield on the nation’s 10 percent bonds due July 2024
fell seven basis points, or 0.07 percentage point, to 8.2
percent at 10:03 a.m. New York time, according to Colombia’s
stock exchange. That’s its lowest since Jan. 14. The bond’s
price jumped 0.631 centavo to 114.128 centavos per peso.  Colombia’s consumer prices rose 0.12 percent in April from
the previous month and climbed 2.84 percent from the same month
a year earlier, according to a  report  late yesterday from the
statistics agency. Economists had forecast a monthly increase of
0.36 percent and an annual inflation rate of 3.08 percent,
according to the median forecast of analysts surveyed by
Bloomberg. Monthly inflation slowed from 0.27 percent in March.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Andrea Jaramillo in Bogota at 
